com.avaya.csta.binding

Class RedirectMediaRequest

  • java.lang.Object
    • ch.ecma.csta.CastorObject
      • com.avaya.csta.binding.RedirectMediaRequest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class RedirectMediaRequest
extends ch.ecma.csta.CastorObject
implements java.io.Serializable
    Used to redirect the media stream of a previously-registered terminal. This can only be used when in client media mode, and then only to change the destination of the RTP and RTCP stream and, optionally, the codec and encryption parameters. The use of this call to switch from server media mode to client media mode, or vice versa, is not supported.

    If you wish to use the same codec and encryption parameters for the new recipient of the media stream as for the original one, call setUsePreviousValues with a true Boolean value. Otherwise, you may specify any valid, non-null values for the codec and encryption parameters.

    If there is a problem with the request, an exception is thrown. Both a MediaStopEvent and a MediaStartEvent will occur if a call is underway at the time a RedirectMediaRequest is received; otherwise, no media event will occur. If the extension is in multiple calls, the Communication Manager will send a MediaStopEvent for each of the calls. However, the Communication Manager will initially send a MediaStartEvent only for the active call. A MediaStartEvent for a held call will be sent once the held call becomes active.

    Note: when using RedirectMediaRequest, the programmer is responsible for ensuring that the RTP and RTCP addresses specified in localMediaInfo are correct. If they are incorrect, then the media stream will be directed to the incorrect address and will be lost.

    Since the RegistrationServices.redirectMedia is a synchronous call, this request will block while waiting for a response. If it is desirable that the application thread be able to continue processing while waiting for the response, consider using AsynchronousServices (Java API only) to process the RedirectMediaRequest.

    Note: there is a limitation (bug) in CM that requires the RedirectMedia request to specify a different IP address for the RTP; otherwise the request will be ignored (a change in the port number only is ignored by CM). Thus, if you want to change only the port number of the media destination, it must be done in two steps:

    • Send a RedirectMedia request specifying an IP address of "0.0.0.0". This will cause CM to stop the media stream to the original client destination (but leave the call up).
    • Send a 2nd RedirectMedia request specifying the actual new destination for the media stream. Since this will involve specifying a new IP address (as well as a new port), CM will process this request correctly.

    The RedirectMediaRequest request has these parameters:

    RedirectMediaRequest Parameters
    device Mandatory Unique identifier of phone/extension that was originally registered in MediaMode.CLIENT.
    usePreviousValues Optional Indicates whether to use the codec and encryption parameters specified in the localMediaInfo parameter, or to re-use the codec and encryption parameters previously specified in the RegisterTerminalRequest. Setting this parameter to true indicates that the codec and encryption parameters that were provided in the RegisterTerminalRequest (or a previous RedirectMediaRequest) should be re-used. If false, then the codec and encryption parameters may be optionally specified in the localMediaInfo parameter, as they are in RegisterTerminalRequest. This parameter is of type boolean and defaults to false.
    localMediaInfo Mandatory This parameter – specifically, its RTP and RTCP addresses and ports – indicates where the device's media stream should be redirected. Depending on the value of the usePreviousValues parameter, it may also indicate which codec and encryption parameters to use. Note: there is also a parameter available which allows you to specify a new RTP packetSize. However, the packetSize is actually controlled by Communication Manager, not by the client. Thus, any value specified in the packetSize parameter will be ignored.

    The localMediaInfo parameter is of type MediaInfo.

    MediaInfo Parameters
    rtpAddress Mandatory Specifies the IP address to which the RTP stream should be redirected. Specify an even UDP port number.
    rtcpAddress Mandatory Specifies the IP address to which RTCP messages should be redirected. Specify the odd UDP port that immediately follows the RTP port you provided.
    codecs Conditional The preferred set of codecs to be used for media coming to the device and media coming from the device. If usePreviousValues is true, then this parameter is prohibited; otherwise it is optional. Possible values are:
    • MediaConstants.G711A (G.711 A-law)
    • MediaConstants.G711U (G.711 Mu-law)
    • MediaConstants.G729
    • MediaConstants.G729A
    • MediaConstants.G723
    Defaults to G.711 A-law and Mu-law, in that order. The G.723 codec may be used only for Client Media Mode (i.e. where the RTP stream is directed to a machine other than the CMAPI connector server and is handled by the application). Multiple codecs can be listed in preferential order. However, a mixture of G.711, G.729 and G.723 cannot be in the list (i.e., the list may contain one or more G.711 codecs or one or more G.729 codecs, but not a mixture of G.711 and G.729). Also, no conversion between G.711 and G.729 (or G.723) is provided by this API. To choose an appropriate codec set, you may wish to first determine how the device's network region and codecs are administered on Communication Manager. This set should consist of only codecs administered for the device's network region.
    encryption Conditional Specifies a list of encryption algorithms supported for media (RTP). If usePreviousValues is true, then this parameter is prohibited; otherwise, it is optional. Possible values include MediaConstants.AES ("aes") and/or MediaConstants.NOENCRYPTION ("none"). This encryption list specifies the capabilities of the CMAPI endpoint. The actual algorithm that is chosen for a call is dependent on the administered list in Communication Manager. Administration of Media Encryption is done in the Communication Manager ip-codec-set form.
    packetSize Conditional Specifies the size of the RTP packets in milliseconds. This parameter is actually controlled by Communication Manager - if specified here, it will be ignored.

    The RedirectMediaResponse indicates the outcome of the request.

    If your application will control the media stream, then it will also need to monitor the media events. The Media Events that may be caused by a RedirectMediaRequest request include:

    • MediaStartEvent
    • MediaStopEvent

    Negative Acknowledgements:

    • operation:invalidDeviceID - Sent if there is no station associated with the device ID specified.
    • stateIncompatibility:invalidDeviceState - Sent if the device is in the wrong state.
    • operation:invalidParameterValue - Sent if the request is NULL.
    • operation:generic - Sent if there is an operation error such as a socket IO error.
    • unspecified - Sent an implementation-specific error occurs.
    Version:
    $Revision$ $Date$

      • getUsePreviousValues

        public java.lang.Boolean getUsePreviousValues()
        Returns the value of field 'usePreviousValues'. The field 'usePreviousValues' has the following description: Indicates whether to use the codec and encryption parameters supplied in a previous localMediaInfo parameter. It is provided to allow programmers to avoid specifying any codec or encryption parameters that were provided in the RegisterTerminalRequest. If false, then the codec and encryption parameters are optional, as they are in RegisterTerminalRequest. If true, then the codec and encryption parameters are prohibited, and the values for those parameters determined at registration time will be provided by the server.

        This parameter is of type boolean and defaults to false.

        Optional.
